revision.text:
{{about|the [[Modern Standard Arabic]] phonology|other regional dialects' phonologies|Varieties of Arabic|the phonology of the medieval language|Classical Arabic#Phonology}} {{selfref|For assistance with IPA transcriptions of Arabic for Wikipedia articles, see [[Help:IPA/Arabic]].}} {{IPA notice}} {{Contains Arabic text}} While many languages have numerous dialects that differ in [[phonology]], the contemporary spoken [[Arabic language]] is more properly described as a [[varieties of Arabic|continuum of varieties]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirchhoff|Vergyri|2005|p=38}}</ref> This article deals primarily with [[Modern Standard Arabic]] (MSA), which is the standard variety shared by educated speakers throughout Arabic-speaking regions. MSA is used in writing in formal print media and orally in newscasts, speeches and formal declarations of numerous types.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Kirchhoff|Vergyri|2005|pp=38–39}}</ref>
Modern Standard Arabic has 28 [[consonant]] [[phoneme]]s and 6 [[vowel]] phonemes (8 vowels in most [[Varieties of Arabic|modern dialects]]). All phonemes contrast between "[[emphatic consonant|emphatic]]" ([[uvularized]]) consonants and non-emphatic ones. Some of these phonemes have coalesced in the various modern dialects, while new phonemes have been introduced through borrowing or phonemic splits. A "phonemic quality of length" applies to consonants as well as vowels.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Holes|2004|p=57}}</ref>{{fix|text=does the source use the term 'uvularized'?|date=March 2017}}
==Vowels== [[File:Arabic vowels (Monophthongs).png|thumb|<!--Don't use the svg version as it has wrong vowel values; short and long values aren't the same for that particular dialect--> Vowel chart representing the pronunciation of long vowels by a Palestinian speaker educated in Beirut. From {{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=38}} (Notice that these values vary between regions across North Africa and West Asia)]] [[File:Arabic vowels (Diphthongs).svg|thumb|Vowel chart representing the pronunciation of diphthongs by a Palestinian speaker educated in Beirut. From {{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=38}}]] Modern Standard Arabic has six vowel phonemes forming three pairs of corresponding short and long vowels ({{IPA|/a, aː, i, iː, u, uː/}}). Many spoken varieties also include {{IPA|/oː/}} and {{IPA|/eː/}}. Modern Standard Arabic has two diphthongs (formed by a combination of short {{IPA|/a/}} with the semivowels {{IPA|/j/}} and {{IPA|/w/}}) in Classical Arabic with no allophones. [[Allophony]] in different dialects of Arabic can occur, and is partially conditioned by neighboring consonants within the same word. As a general rule, for example, {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/aː/}} are:
* {{IPA|/a, aː/}} ** retracted to {{IPAblink|ɑ}} in the environment of a neighboring {{IPA|/r/}}, {{IPA|/q/}} or an [[emphatic consonant]] (one that is [[uvularized]], though customarily transcribed as if [[pharyngealized]]): {{IPA|/sˤ/}}, {{IPA|/dˤ/}}, {{IPA|/tˤ/}}, {{IPA|/ðˤ/}}, {{IPA|/ɫ/}} and in a few regional standard pronunciations also {{IPA|/x/}} and {{IPA|/ɣ/}};<ref name="Thelwall 1990 39">{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=39}}</ref> ** only in Iraq and the [[Arab States of the Persian Gulf|Persian Gulf]]: {{IPAblink|ɐ}} before a word boundary;<ref name="Thelwall 1990 39"/> ** advanced to {{IPAblink|æ}} in the environment of most consonants: *** [[labial consonants]] ({{IPA|/m/}}, {{IPA|/b/}} and {{IPA|/f/}}), *** plain (non-emphatic) [[coronal consonant]]s with the exception of {{IPA|/r/}} ({{IPA|/θ/}}, {{IPA|/ð/}}, {{IPA|/n/}}, {{IPA|/t/}}, {{IPA|/d/}}, {{IPA|/s/}}, {{IPA|/z/}}, {{IPA|/l/}}, {{IPA|/ʃ/}} and {{IPA|/d͡ʒ~ɡ~ʒ/}}) *** [[pharyngeal consonant]]s ({{IPA|/ħ/}} and {{IPA|/ʕ/}}) *** [[glottal consonant]]s ({{IPA|/h/}} and {{IPA|/ʔ/}}) *** {{IPA|/j/}}, {{IPA|/k/}} and {{IPA|/w/}};<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Holes|2004|p=60}}</ref> ** Across [[North Africa]] and West Asia, the allophones {{IPA|[æ]}} and {{IPA|[ɑ]}} may be realized differently, either as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|a}} ~ {{IPA link|ɑ}} ~ {{IPA link|ɛ}}]}}, or both as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|a}} ~ {{IPA link|ä}}]}} ** In northwestern Africa, the open front vowel {{IPAslink|æ}} is raised to {{IPAblink|ɛ}} or {{IPAblink|e}}. * {{IPA|/i, iː, u, uː/}} ** Across North Africa and West Asia, {{IPA|/i/}} may be realized as {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ɪ}} ~ {{IPA link|e}} ~ {{IPA link|ɨ}}]}} before or adjacent to emphatic consonants and {{IPAblink|q}}, {{IPAblink|r}}, {{IPAblink|ħ}}, {{IPAblink|ʕ}}. {{IPA|/u/}} can also have different realizations, i.e. {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ʊ}} ~ {{IPA link|o}} ~ {{IPA link|ʉ}}]}}. Sometimes with one value for each vowel in both short and long [[Vowel length|lengths]] or two different values for each short and long lengths. They are distinct phonemes in loan words. ** In Egypt, close vowels have different values; short initial or medial: {{IPAblink|e}},&nbsp;{{IPAblink|o}} ← instead of {{IPA|/i,&nbsp;u/}}. {{IPA|/i~ɪ/}} and {{IPA|/u~ʊ/}} completely become {{IPA|[e]}} and {{IPA|[o]}} respectively in some other particular dialects. Unstressed final long {{IPA|/aː,&nbsp;iː,&nbsp;uː/}} are most often shortened or reduced: {{IPA|/aː/}}&nbsp;→&nbsp;{{IPA|[æ ~ ɑ]}}, {{IPA|/iː/}}&nbsp;→&nbsp;{{IPA|[i]}}, {{IPA|/uː/}}&nbsp;→&nbsp;{{IPA|[o~u]}}.
{| class="wikitable nowrap" style="text-align: center;" |+ Example words<ref name="Thelwall 1990 38">{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=38}}</ref> ! ! colspan="2" | short ! colspan="2" | long |- ! i | {{rtl-lang|ar|عِدْ}} {{IPA|/ʕid/}}|| "promise!" || {{rtl-lang|ar|عِيد}} {{IPA|/ʕiːd/}} || "holiday" |- ! u | {{rtl-lang|ar|عُدّ}} {{IPA|/ʕudd/}} || "count (command)" ||{{rtl-lang|ar|عُود}} {{IPA|/ʕuːd/}} || "lute" |- ! a | {{rtl-lang|ar|َعَدّ}} {{IPA|/ʕadd/}} || "counted" || {{rtl-lang|ar|عَاد}} {{IPA|/ʕaːd/}} || "came back" |- ! aj | | | {{rtl-lang|ar|عَيْن}} {{IPA|/ʕajn/}} || "eye" |- ! aw | | | {{rtl-lang|ar|عَوْد}} {{IPA|/ʕawd/}} || "return" |}
However, the actual rules governing vowel-retraction are a good deal more complex, and have relatively little in the way of an agreed-upon standard, as there are often competing notions of what constitutes a "prestige" form.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abd-El-Jawad|1987|p=359}}</ref> Often, even highly proficient speakers will import the vowel-retraction rules from their native dialects.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Abd-El-Jawad|1987|p=361}}</ref> Thus, for example, in the Arabic of someone from Cairo emphatic consonants will affect every vowel between word boundaries, whereas certain Saudi speakers exhibit emphasis only on the vowels adjacent to an emphatic consonant.<ref name="Watson 1999 290">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|1999|p=290}}</ref> Certain speakers (most notably Levantine speakers) exhibit a degree of asymmetry in leftward vs. rightward spread of vowel-retraction.<ref name="Watson 1999 290"/><ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Davis|1995|p=466}}</ref>
{{col-begin}} {{col-2}} {| class="wikitable" border="1" style="text-align: center;" |+Vowel phonemes of [[Modern Standard Arabic]] & [[Classical Arabic]] ! rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" |Short ! colspan="2" |Long |- ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- style="text-align: center;" ![[Close vowel|Close]] | {{IPA|/i/}} | {{IPA|/u/}} | {{IPA|/iː/}} | {{IPA|/uː/}} |- style="text-align: center;" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | colspan="2" |{{IPA|/a/}} | colspan="2" |{{IPA|/aː/}} |- ![[Diphthong]]s | colspan="4" |{{IPA|/aw/}}, {{IPA|/aj/}} |}
{{col-2}} {| class="wikitable" border="1" style="text-align: center;" |+most common vowel system among [[Arabic dialects]] ! rowspan="2" | ! colspan="2" |Short ! colspan="2" |Long |- ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] ![[Front vowel|Front]] ![[Back vowel|Back]] |- style="text-align: center;" ![[Close vowel|Close]] | rowspan="2" |{{IPA|/i/}} | rowspan="2" |{{IPA|/u/}} | {{IPA|/iː/}} | {{IPA|/uː/}} |- style="text-align: center;" ![[Mid vowel|Mid]] | {{IPA|/eː/}} | {{IPA|/oː/}} |- style="text-align: center;" ![[Open vowel|Open]] | colspan="2" |{{IPA|/a/}} | colspan="2" |{{IPA|/aː/}} |- !Diphthongs | colspan="4" |{{IPA|/aw/}}, {{IPA|/aj/}} |} {{col-end}}
The final [[syllable weight|heavy syllable]] of a root is stressed.<ref name="Thelwall 1990 38"/>
However, the pronunciation of [[loanword]]s is highly dependent on the speaker's native variety.
The long mid vowels {{IPA|/oː/}} and {{IPA|/eː/}} appear in to be phonemic in most varieties of Arabic, and they can be used in Modern Standard Arabic in some stable loanwords or foreign names,<ref name="EMSA1">Elementary Modern Standard Arabic: Volume 1, by Peter F. Abboud (Editor), Ernest N. McCarus (Editor)</ref> e.g. {{lang|ar|كوكاكولا}} {{IPA|/ko(ː)kaˈkoːla/}} ('Coca-Cola'), {{lang|ar|شوكولاتة}} {{IPA|/ʃo(ː)ko(ː)ˈlaːta/}} ('chocolate'), {{lang|ar|دكتور}} {{IPA|/dukˈtoːr/}} or {{IPA|/dokˈtoːr/}} ('doctor'), {{lang|ar|جون}} {{IPA|/(d)ʒoːn/}} ('[[John (first name)|John]]'), {{lang|ar|توم}} {{IPA|/to(ː)m/}} ('Tom'), {{lang|ar|بلجيكا}} {{IPA|/belˈ(d)ʒiːka/}} ('Belgium'), {{lang|ar|سكرتير}} {{IPA|/sekreˈteːr/}} or {{IPA|/sekerˈteːr/}} ('secretary'), etc. Foreign words often have a liberal sprinkling of long vowels, as their word shapes do not conform to standardized prescriptive pronunciations written by letters for short vowels.<ref name="TYA">Teach Yourself Arabic, by Jack Smart (Author), Frances Altorfer (Author)</ref> When in need the letters {{lang|ar|ي}} or {{lang|ar|و}} are always used to render the long vowels {{IPA|/eː/}} and {{IPA|/oː/}}.
==Consonants== {{See also|Arabic letters|sun and moon letters}}
Even in the most formal of conventions, pronunciation depends upon a speaker's background.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Holes|2004|p=58}}</ref> Nevertheless, the number and phonetic character of most of the 28 consonants has a broad degree of regularity among Arabic-speaking regions. Note that Arabic is particularly rich in [[uvular consonant|uvular]], [[pharyngeal consonant|pharyngeal]], and [[pharyngealization|pharyngealized]] ("[[emphatic consonant|emphatic]]") sounds. The emphatic [[coronal consonant|coronal]]s ({{IPA|/sˤ/}}, {{IPA|/dˤ/}}, {{IPA|/tˤ/}}, and {{IPA|/ðˤ/}}) cause [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]] of emphasis to adjacent non-emphatic coronal consonants.{{citation needed|date=September 2008}} The phonemes {{IPA|/p/}} ⟨[[Pe (Persian letter)|پ]]⟩ and {{IPA|/v/}} ⟨[[Ve (Arabic letter)|ڤ]]⟩ (not used by all speakers) are not considered to be part of the phonemic inventory, as they exist only in foreign words and they can be pronounced as {{IPA|/b/}} ⟨[[ب]]⟩ and {{IPA|/f/}} ⟨[[ف]]⟩ respectively depending on the speaker.<ref name="TYA"/><ref name=Wehr>Hans Wehr, ''[[Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic]]'' (transl. of ''Arabisches Wörterbuch für die Schriftsprache der Gegenwart'', 1952)</ref>. The standard pronunciation of ⟨[[ج]]⟩ {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} varies regionally, most prominently {{IPAblink|d͡ʒ}} in the [[Arabian Peninsula]], parts of the [[Levant]], [[Iraq]], northern [[Algeria]] and [[Sudan]], it is also considered as the predominant pronunciation of Literary Arabic outside the Arab world, {{IPAblink|ʒ}} in most of [[Maghreb|Northwest Africa]] and the Levant, and {{IPAblink|g}} only in [[Egypt]]. {| class="wikitable" style="text-align:center" |+ Modern Standard Arabic consonant phonemes ! colspan="2" rowspan="2" | ! rowspan="2" | [[Labial consonant|Labial]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Dental consonant|Dental]] ! colspan="2" | [[Denti-alveolar consonant|Denti-alveolar]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Palatal consonant|Palatal]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Velar consonant|Velar]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Uvular consonant|Uvular]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Pharyngeal consonant|Pharyngeal]] ! rowspan="2" | [[Glottal consonant|Glottal]] |- style="font-size: 80%;" ! plain ! [[Emphatic consonant|emphatic]]{{efn|Emphatic consonants are pronounced with the back of the tongue approaching the [[human pharynx|pharynx]] (see [[pharyngealization]]). They are pronounced with [[velarization]] by the Iraqi and Arabic Gulf speakers.{{fact|date=June 2016}} {{IPA|/q/}}, {{IPA|/ħ/}}, and {{IPA|/ʕ/}} can be considered the emphatic counterparts to {{IPA|/k/}}, {{IPA|/h/}}, and {{IPA|/ʔ/}} respectively.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=44}}</ref>}} |- ! colspan="2" style="text-align: left;" | [[Nasal stop|Nasal]] | {{IPA link|m}} | | {{IPA link|n}} | | | | | | |- ! rowspan="2" style="text-align: left;" | [[Stop consonant|Stop]] ! style="text-align: left; font-size: 80%;" | [[Voiceless consonant|voiceless]] | ({{IPA link|p}}){{efn|name=pv|{{IPA|/p, v/}} are not necessarily pronounced by all Arabic speakers, but are often pronounced in names and loanwords. Foreign sounds {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/v/}} are usually transcribed as {{lang|ar|ب}} {{IPA|/b/}} and {{lang|ar|ف}} {{IPA|/f/}}, respectively. In some words, they are pronounced as in the original language ({{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/v/}}), e.g. {{lang|ar|باكستان}} or {{lang|fa|پاکستان}} {{IPA|/pa(ː)kistaːn, ba(ː)kistaːn/}} "Pakistan", {{lang|ar|فيروس}} or {{lang|ar|ڤيروس}} {{IPA|/vi(ː)ru(ː)s, vajru(ː)s/}} "virus", etc. Sometimes the Persian letter (with 3 dots) {{lang|fa|ﭖ}} {{IPA|/p/}} and a modified {{lang|ar|ﭪ}} {{IPA|/v/}} letter are used for this purpose. As these letters are not present on standard keyboards, they are simply written with {{lang|ar|ب}} {{IPA|/b/}} and {{lang|ar|ف}} {{IPA|/f/}}, e.g. both {{lang|ar|نوفمبر}} and {{lang|ar|نوڤمبر}} {{IPA|/nu(ː)fambar/}}, {{IPA|/novambar, -ber/}} or {{IPA|/nofember/}} "November", both {{lang|ar|كاپريس}} and {{lang|ar|كابريس}} {{IPA|/ka(ː)pri(ː)s, ka(ː)bri(ː)s/}} "caprice" can be used.<ref name="TYA"/><ref name=Wehr>Hans Wehr, ''[[Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic]]'' (transl. of ''Arabisches Wörterbuch für die Schriftsprache der Gegenwart'', 1952)</ref> The use of both sounds may be considered marginal and Arabs may pronounce the words interchangeably; besides, many loanwords have become Arabicized. (November is often نُوَمْبِرْ, {{IPA|/nuwamber/}}, eliding the sound entirely.)}} | | {{IPA link|t̪|t}}{{efn|name=dental|Depending on the region, the plosives are either [[alveolar plosive|alveolar]] or [[dental consonant|dental]].}} | {{IPA link|tˤ}}{{efn|name=ta-dad|{{lang|ar|ض}} {{IPA|/dˤ/}} and {{lang|ar|ط}} {{IPA|/tˤ/}} are pronounced as {{IPA|[d̪ˠ]}} and {{IPA|[t̪ˠ]}}, respectively, in Iraq and only in the eastern part of the Arabian Peninsula.{{fact|date=June 2016}}}} | | {{IPA link|k}} | {{IPA link|q}}{{efn|The Sudanese usually pronounce {{IPAslink|q}} ({{lang|ar|[[ق]]}}) as {{IPAblink|ɢ}} even in Literary Arabic.}} | | {{IPA link|ʔ}} |- ! style="text-align: left; font-size: 80%;" | [[Voiced consonant|voiced]] | {{IPA link|b}} | | {{IPA link|d̪|d}}{{efn|name=dental}} | {{IPA link|dˤ}}{{efn|name=ta-dad}} | |({{IPA link|g}}){{efn|In Modern Standard Arabic {{IPA|/g/}} is used as a marginal phoneme to pronounce some dialectal and loan words. On the other hand it is considered a native [[phoneme]] or [[allophone]] in most modern Arabic dialects, mostly as a variant of {{lang|ar|ق}} {{IPA|/q/}} (as in [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Arabian Peninsula]] and [[Northwest African]] dialects) or as a variant of {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} {{lang|ar|ج}} (as in Egyptian and a number of Yemeni and Omani dialects). It is also considered a separate foreign phoneme that appears only in loanwords, as in most urban [[Levant]]ine dialects where {{lang|ar|ق}} is {{IPA|/ʔ/}} and {{lang|ar|ج}} is {{IPA|/d͡ʒ~ʒ/}}.
Foreign words containing {{IPAslink|ɡ}} may be transcribed more commonly with {{rtl-lang|ar|[[ج]]}}, {{rtl-lang|ar|[[غ]]}}, {{rtl-lang|ar|[[ق]]}} or {{rtl-lang|ar|[[ك]]}} or less commonly {{script/Arabic|[[ݣ]]}} (used in Morocco) or {{script/Arabic|ڨ}} (used in Tunisian and Algeria), mainly depending on the regional spoken [[varieties of Arabic|variety of Arabic]] or the commonly diacriticized Arabic letter.}} | | | |- ! rowspan="2" style="text-align: left;" | [[Fricative]] ! style="text-align: left; font-size: 80%;" | [[Voiceless consonant|voiceless]] | {{IPA link|f}} | {{IPA link|θ}}{{efn|name=tha-dha|In nonstandard pronunciations and some dialects, {{IPA|/θ/}} and {{IPA|/ð/}} may be merged to {{IPAblink|s}} and {{IPAblink|z}}, respectively.}} | {{IPA link|s̪|s}} | {{IPA link|sˤ}} | {{IPA link|ʃ}} | colspan="2" | {{IPA link|x}} ~ {{IPA link|χ}}{{efn|name=velar|In most regions, uvular fricatives of the classical period have become velar or post-velar.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=18}}</ref>}} | {{IPA link|ħ}}{{efn|name=pharyngeal|The "[[voiced pharyngeal fricative]]" {{IPA|/ʕ/}} ({{lang|ar|ع}}) is described as neither pharyngeal nor fricative, but a [[creaky voice|creaky-voiced]] [[epiglottal consonant|epiglottal]] [[approximant]].<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ladefoged|Maddieson|1996|pp=167–168}}</ref> Its unvoiced counterpart {{IPA|/ħ/}} ({{lang|ar|ح}}) is likewise epiglottal, although it is a true fricative. Thelwall asserts that the sound of {{lang|ar|ع}} is actually a pharyngealized [[glottal stop]] {{IPA|[ʔˤ]}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990}}, citing {{Harvcoltxt|Gairdner|1925}}, {{Harvcoltxt|Al Ani|1970}}, and {{Harvcoltxt|Käster|1981}}.</ref> Similarly, {{Harvcoltxt|McCarthy|1994}} points to dialectal and idiolectal variation between stop and continuant variations of {{IPA|/ʕ/}} in Iraq and Kuwait, noting that the distinction is superficial for Arabic speakers and carries "no phonological consequences."<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|McCarthy|1994|pp=194–195}}</ref>}} |[[Voiceless glottal fricative|h]] |- ! style="text-align: left; font-size: 80%;" | [[Voiced consonant|voiced]] | ({{IPA link|v}}){{efn|name=pv}} | {{IPA link|ð}}{{efn|name=tha-dha}} | {{IPA link|z̪|z}} | {{IPA link|ðˤ}} | | colspan="2" | {{IPA link|ɣ}} ~ {{IPA link|ʁ}}{{efn|name=velar}} | {{IPA link|ʕ}}{{efn|name=pharyngeal}} | |- ! style="text-align: left;" | [[Affricate consonant|Affricate]] ! style="text-align: left; font-size: 80%;" | [[Voiced consonant|voiced]] | | | | | {{IPA link|d͡ʒ}}{{efn|The [[phoneme]] represented by the Arabic letter ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ǧīm}}'' ({{lang|ar|[[ج]]}}) has a couple of regional colloquial pronunciations that might differ from the Standard pronunciation: {{IPAblink|ɡ}} in most of Egypt and some regions in southern Yemen and southwestern Oman, which is a characteristic of colloquial [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]] and southern Yemeni dialects.<ref name="Watson 2002 16">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=16}}</ref> In Morocco and western Algeria, it is pronounced as {{IPAblink|ɡ}} in some words, especially colloquially. In certain regions of the Persian Gulf it might be realized colloquially as {{IPAblink|j}}. In some [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudanese]] and [[Yemeni Arabic|Yemeni dialects]], it may be either {{IPA|[ɡʲ]}} or {{IPAblink|ɟ}}.}} | | | | |- ! colspan="2" style="text-align: left;" | [[Trill consonant|Trill]] | | | {{IPA link|r}}{{efn|Emphatic {{IPA|/r/}} exists Northwestern African pronunciations. The trill {{IPA|/r/}} is sometimes reduced to a single vibration when single, but it remains potentially a trill, not a [[alveolar flap|flap]] {{IPA|[ɾ]}}: the pronunciation of this single trill is between a trill {{IPA|[r]}} and a flap {{IPA|[ɾ]}}. <r> is in free variation between a trill {{IPA|/r/}} and a [[alveolar flap|flap]] {{IPA|[ɾ]}} in Egyptian and Levantine dialects.}} | | | | | | |- ! colspan="2" style="text-align: left;" | [[Approximant]] | | | {{IPA link|l}} | ({{IPA link|ɫ}}){{efn|In most pronunciations, {{IPA|/ɫ/}} as a phoneme occurs in a handful of loanwords. It also occurs in {{lang|ar|الله}} ''[[Allah]]'' {{IPA|/ʔaɫˈɫaːh/}}, the name of God,<ref name="Watson 2002 16"/> except when it follows long or short {{IPA|/i/}} when it is not emphatic: {{lang|ar|بسم الله}} ''[[Basmala|{{transl|ar|DIN|bismi l-lāh}}]]'' {{IPA|/bis.milˈlaːh/}}<!--an approximant can't be written with []--> ("in the name of God").<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Holes|2004|p=95}}</ref> However, {{IPA|/ɫ/}} is absent in many places, such as Egypt, and is more widespread in certain dialects, such as [[Iraqi Arabic|Iraqi]], where the uvulars have velarized surrounding instances of {{IPA|/l/}} in certain environments. {{IPA|/ɫ/}} also assumes phonemic status more commonly in pronunciations influenced by such dialects. Furthermore, {{IPA|/ɫ/}} also occurs as an allophone of {{IPA|/l/}} in the environment of emphatic consonants when the two are not separated by {{IPA|/i/}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Ferguson|1956|p=449}}</ref>}} | {{IPA link|j}} | {{IPA link|w}} | | | |}
{{notelist}}
Long ([[geminate]] or double) consonants are pronounced exactly like short consonants, but last longer. In Arabic, they are called ''mushaddadah'' ("strengthened", marked with a [[shaddah]]), but they are not actually pronounced any "stronger". Between a long consonant and a pause, an [[epenthetic]] {{IPA|[ə]}} occurs,<ref name="Thelwall 1990 38"/> but this is only common across regions in West Asia.
==Phonotactics== {{unreferenced section|date=October 2014}} Arabic syllable structure can be summarized as follows, in which parentheses enclose optional components: * (C<sub>1</sub>) (S<sub>1</sub>) V (S<sub>2</sub>) (C<sub>2</sub> (C<sub>3</sub>))
Arabic [[Syllable#Structure|syllable structure]] consists of an optional syllable onset, consisting of one or two consonants; an obligatory syllable nucleus, consisting of a vowel optionally preceded by and/or followed by a [[semivowel]]; and an optional syllable coda, consisting of one or two consonants. The following restrictions apply:
* Onset ** First consonant (C<sub>1</sub>): Can be any consonant, including a liquid ({{IPA|/l, r/}}). (Onset is composed only of one consonant; consonant clusters are only found in [[loanwords]], sometimes an epenthetic {{IPA|/a/}} is inserted between consonants.) * Nucleus ** Semivowel (S<sub>1</sub>) ** Vowel (V) ** Semivowel (S<sub>2</sub>) * Coda ** First consonant (C<sub>2</sub>): Can be any consonant. ** Second consonant (C<sub>3</sub>): Can also be any consonant.
==Word stress==
The placement of word stress in Arabic varies considerably from one dialect to another, and has been the focus of extensive research and debate.
In determining stress, Arabic distinguishes three types of syllables:<ref>Watson, JCE (2011) Word stress in Arabic. In: The Blackwell companion to phonology. Wiley-Blackwell, Oxford, 2990-3019 (p. 2991), http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/75747/.</ref>
* Light: ** An open syllable containing a short vowel (i.e. CV), such as ''wa'' 'and' * Heavy: ** An open syllable containing a long vowel (i.e. CVV), such as ''sā.fara'' 'he travelled' ** A closed syllable containing a short vowel followed by one consonant (i.e. CVC), such as ''min'' 'from' or ''ka.tab.tu'' 'I wrote' * Super-heavy: ** A closed syllable containing a long vowel followed by one consonant (i.e. CVVC), such as ''bāb#'' 'door' or ''mād.dun'' 'stretching (NOM)' ** A closed syllable containing a vowel of any length followed by two consonants (i.e. CVCC, CVVCC), such as ''bint#'' 'girl' or ''mādd#'' 'stretching'
The word stress of Classical Arabic has been the subject of debate. However, there is consensus as to the general rule, even though there are some exceptions. A simple rule of thumb is that word-stress falls on the penultimate syllable of a word if that syllable is closed, and otherwise on the antepenultimate.<ref>Kees Versteegh, ''The Arabic Language'' (Edinburgh: Edinburgh University Press, 1997), p. 90.</ref>
A more precise description is J. C. E. Watson's. Here the stressed syllable follows the marker ' and variant rules are in brackets:<ref>Watson, JCE (2011) Word stress in Arabic. In: The Blackwell companion to phonology. Wiley-Blackwell, Oxford, 2990-3019 (p. 3003), http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/75747/.</ref>
# Stress a pre-[[Pausa|pausal]] superheavy (CVVC, CVVGG, or CVCC) syllable: {{IPA|[kiˈtaːb]}} ‘book’, {{IPA|[ˈmaːdd]}} ‘stretching (MASC SG)’, {{IPA|[ʃaːˈribt]}} ‘I/you (MASC SG) drank’. # Otherwise, stress the rightmost (ending) non-final heavy (CVV, CVC, or CVVG) syllable (up to the antepenult): {{IPA|[daˈrasnaː]}} ‘we learnt’, {{IPA|[ṣaːˈbuːnun]}} ‘soap (NOM)’, {{IPA|[ˈmaktabah]}} ‘library’, {{IPA|[ˈmaːddun]}} ‘stretching (NOM)’, {{IPA|[ˈmaktabatun]}} ‘library’ (non-pause) (or {{IPA|[makˈtabatun]}}). # Otherwise, stress the leftmost (beginning) CV syllable (or antepenult): {{IPA|[ˈkataba]}} ‘he wrote’, {{IPA|[ˈkatabatuhu]}} ‘library’ (or {{IPA|[kataˈbatuhu]}}).
Modern Arabic dialects all maintain rules (1) and (2). But if there is neither a final superheavy syllable nor a heavy penultimate syllable, their behaviour varies. Thus in Palestinian, rule (3) is instead 'otherwise stress the first syllable (up to the antepenult): {{IPA|[ˈkatab]}} ‘he wrote’, {{IPA|[ˈzalama]}} ‘man’', whereas the basic rules of Cairene (to which there are exceptions) are:<ref>Watson, JCE (2011) Word stress in Arabic. In: The Blackwell companion to phonology. Wiley-Blackwell, Oxford, 2990-3019 (pp. 2993, 3004), http://eprints.whiterose.ac.uk/75747/.</ref>
# Stress a superheavy ultima. # Otherwise, stress a heavy penult. # Otherwise, stress the penult or antepenult, whichever is separated by an even number of syllables from the rightmost non-final heavy syllable, or, if there is no non-final heavy syllable, from the left boundary of the word.
==Local variations of Modern Standard Arabic==
[[varieties of Arabic|Spoken varieties]] differ from [[Classical Arabic]] and [[Modern Standard Arabic]] not only in grammar but also in pronunciation. Outside of the Arabian peninsula, a major linguistic division is between ''sedentary'' varieties, largely urban varieties. Inside the Arabian peninsula and in Iraq, the two types are less distinct; but the language of the urbanized [[Hijaz]], at least, strongly looks like a conservative sedentary variety.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}}
Some examples of variation:
;Consonants
{| class="wikitable" |+Different representations for some phonemes that did not exist in Classical Arabic ! rowspan="2" |Phoneme ! colspan="10" |Letters |- ![[Moroccan Arabic|Moroccan]] ![[Tunisian Arabic|Tunisian]] ![[Algerian Arabic|Algerian]] ![[Hejazi Arabic|Hejazi]] ![[Najdi Arabic|Najdi]] ![[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]] ![[Levantine Arabic|Levantine]] ![[Palestinian Arabic|Palestinian]] ![[Mesopotamian Arabic|Iraqi]] ![[Gulf Arabic|Gulf]] |- style="text-align:center;" |{{IPAslink|g}} |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڭ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[Gaf|گ]]}}</big> | colspan="2" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڨ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڧ|ڧـ]] [[ڧ|ـڧـ]] [[ٯ|ـٯ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ق]]}}</big> | colspan="2" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ق]]}}</big> |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}}{{efn|In Egypt, when there is a need to transcribe {{IPA|/ʒ/}} or {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}}, both are approximated to {{IPA|[ʒ]}} using [[چ]].|name=Egyptian}}</big> |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[غ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}}{{efn|{{IPA|/g/}} is not part of the phonemic inventory of urban Levantine Arabic dialects (Lebanese, Syrian and Palestinian).|name=Levantine}}</big> |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[چ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}}{{efn|{{IPA|/g/}} is not part of the phonemic inventory of urban Levantine Arabic dialects (Lebanese, Syrian and Palestinian).|name=Levantine}}</big> |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[Gaf|گ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ك]]}}</big> |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ق]] / [[گ]]}}</big> |- style="text-align:center;" |{{IPAslink|p}}<sup><small>{{efn|unlike {{IPA|/g/}} and {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}}, {{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/v/}} never appear natively in Arabic dialects, and they are always restricted to loanwords, with their usage depending on the speaker.|name=p and v}}</small></sup> | colspan="10" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[پ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ب]]}}</big> |- style="text-align:center;" |{{IPAslink|v}}<small><sup>{{efn|name=p and v}}</sup></small> | colspan="3" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڥ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڢ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ف]]}}</big> | colspan="7" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڤ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ف]]}}</big> |- style="text-align:center;" |{{IPAslink|t͡ʃ}} |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ڜ]]}}</big> | colspan="7" |<big>{{script/Arabic|تش}}</big> | colspan="2" |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[چ]]}}</big> / <big>{{script/Arabic|[[ك]]}}</big> |} {{notelist}}
In Modern Standard Arabic {{IPA|/g/}} is used as a marginal phoneme to pronounce some dialectal and loan words. On the other hand it is considered a native [[phoneme]] or [[allophone]] in most modern Arabic dialects, mostly as a variant of {{lang|ar|ق}} {{IPA|/q/}} (as in [[Arab states of the Persian Gulf|Arabian Peninsula]] and [[Northwest African]] dialects) or as a variant of {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} {{lang|ar|ج}} (as in Egyptian and a number of Yemeni and Omani dialects). It is also considered a separate foreign phoneme that appears only in loanwords, as in most urban [[Levant]]ine dialects where {{lang|ar|ق}} is {{IPA|/ʔ/}} and {{lang|ar|ج}} is {{IPA|/d͡ʒ~ʒ/}}.
The [[phoneme]] represented by the Arabic letter ''{{transl|ar|DIN|ǧīm}}'' ({{lang|ar|[[ج]]}}) has many standard pronunciations: {{IPAblink|d͡ʒ}} in most of the Arabian Peninsula and as the predominant pronunciation of Literary Arabic outside the Arab world, {{IPAblink|ɡ}} in most of Egypt and some regions in southern Yemen and southwestern Oman. This is also a characteristic of colloquial [[Egyptian Arabic|Egyptian]] and southern Yemeni dialects.<ref name="Watson 2002 16">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=16}}</ref> In Morocco and western Algeria, it is pronounced as {{IPAblink|ɡ}} in some words, especially colloquially. In most north Africa and most of the [[Levant]], the standard is pronounced {{IPAblink|ʒ}}, and in certain regions of the Persian Gulf colloquially with {{IPAblink|j}}. In some [[Sudanese Arabic|Sudanese]] and [[Yemeni Arabic|Yemeni dialects]], it may be either {{IPA|[ɡʲ]}} or {{IPAblink|ɟ}} as it used to be in [[Classical Arabic]].
{{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/v/}} are not necessarily pronounced by all Arabic speakers, but are often pronounced in names and loanwords. Foreign sounds {{IPA|/p/}}, {{IPA|/v/}} are usually transcribed as {{lang|ar|ب}} {{IPA|/b/}} and {{lang|ar|ف}} {{IPA|/f/}}, respectively. In some words, they are pronounced as in the original language ({{IPA|/p/}} and {{IPA|/v/}}), e.g. {{lang|ar|باكستان}} or {{lang|fa|پاکستان}} {{IPA|/pa(ː)kistaːn, ba(ː)kistaːn/}} "Pakistan", {{lang|ar|فيروس}} or {{lang|ar|ڤيروس}} {{IPA|/vi(ː)ru(ː)s, vajru(ː)s/}} "virus", etc. Sometimes the Persian letter (with 3 dots) {{lang|fa|ﭖ}} {{IPA|/p/}} and a modified {{lang|ar|ﭪ}} {{IPA|/v/}} letter are used for this purpose. As these letters are not present on standard keyboards, they are simply written with {{lang|ar|ب}} {{IPA|/b/}} and {{lang|ar|ف}} {{IPA|/f/}}, e.g. both {{lang|ar|نوفمبر}} and {{lang|ar|نوڤمبر}} {{IPA|/nu(ː)fambar/}}, {{IPA|/novambar, -ber/}} or {{IPA|/nofember/}} "November", both {{lang|ar|كاپريس}} and {{lang|ar|كابريس}} {{IPA|/ka(ː)pri(ː)s, ka(ː)bri(ː)s/}} "caprice" can be used.<ref name="TYA"/><ref name=Wehr>Hans Wehr, ''[[Dictionary of Modern Written Arabic]]'' (transl. of ''Arabisches Wörterbuch für die Schriftsprache der Gegenwart'', 1952)</ref> The use of both sounds may be considered marginal and Arabs may pronounce the words interchangeably; besides, many loanwords have become Arabized.
{{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} is another possible loanword phoneme, as in the word {{script/Arabic|سندوتش}} (''sandawitsh'' 'sandwich'), though a number of varieties instead break up the {{IPA|[t]}} and {{IPA|[ʃ]}} sounds with an epenthetic vowel.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|pp=60–62}}, citing Ṣan‘ā’ni and Cairene as examples with and without this phoneme, respectively.</ref> Egyptian Arabic treats {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} as two consonants ({{IPA|[tʃ]}}) and inserts {{IPA|[e]}}, as [{{IPA|teʃ}}C] or [C{{IPA|etʃ}}], when it occurs before or after another consonant. {{IPA|/t͡ʃ/}} is found as normal in [[Iraqi Arabic]] and [[Gulf Arabic]].<ref name="tsh">[http://www.gulfarabic.com/p11_learn_arabic_sounds.php Gulf Arabic Sounds]</ref> Normally the combination <big>{{lang|ar|تش}}</big> (''tā’-shīn'') is used to transliterate the {{IPA|[tʃ]}}. Otherwise Arabic usually substitutes other letters in the transliteration of names and loanwords like the Persian character {{lang|fa|چ}} which is used for writing {{IPA|[tʃ]}}
Other Variations include: * Split of original {{IPA|/r/}} into two phonemes, distinguished primarily by how they affect neighboring vowels. This has progressed the farthest in North Africa. See [[Moroccan Arabic]], [[Algerian Arabic]], [[Tunisian Arabic]] and [[Libyan Arabic]] * Loss of the [[glottal stop]] in places where it is historically attested, as in {{IPA|/samaːʔ/}} → {{IPA|/sama/}}.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}}
; Vowels
* Development of highly distinctive allophones of {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/aː/}}, with highly fronted {{IPA|[a(ː)]}}, {{IPA|[æ(ː)]}} or {{IPA|[ɛ(ː)]}} in non-emphatic contexts, and retracted {{IPA|[ɑ(ː)]}} in emphatic contexts.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} The more extreme distinctions are characteristic of sedentary varieties, while Bedouin and conservative Arabian-peninsula varieties have much closer allophones. In some of the sedentary varieties, the allophones are gradually splitting into new phonemes under the influence of loanwords, where the allophone closest in sound to the source-language vowel often appears regardless of the presence or absence of nearby emphatic consonants.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} * Spread of "emphasis", visible in the backing of phonemic {{IPA|/a(ː)/}}. In conservative varieties of the Arabic peninsula, only {{IPA|/a/}} adjacent to emphatic consonants is affected, while in [[Cairo]], an emphatic consonant anywhere in a word tends to trigger emphatic allophones throughout the entire word.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} Dialects of the Levant are somewhere in between. [[Moroccan Arabic]] is unusual in that {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} have clear emphatic allophones as well (typically lowered, e.g. to {{IPA|[e]}} and {{IPA|[o]}}).{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} * Monophthongization of diphthongs such as {{IPA|/aj/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} to {{IPA|/eː/}} and {{IPA|/oː/}}, respectively ({{IPA|/iː/}} and {{IPA|/uː/}} in parts of the Maghrib, such as in [[Moroccan Arabic]]). Mid vowels may also be present in loanwords such as {{lang|ar|ملبورن}} ({{IPA|/milboːrn/}} [[Melbourne]]), {{lang|ar|سكرتير}} ({{IPA|/sikriteːr/}} '(male) secretary') and {{lang|ar|دكتور}} ({{IPA|/duktoːr/}} 'doctor').<ref name="EMSA1"/> * Raising of word final {{IPA|/a/}} to {{IPA|[e]}}. In some parts of [[Levant]], also word-medial {{IPA|/aː/}} to {{IPA|[eː]}}. See [[Lebanese Arabic]]. * Loss of final short vowels (with {{IPA|/i/}} sometimes remaining), and shortening of final long vowels. This triggered the loss of most Classical Arabic case and mood distinctions.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} * Collapse and deletion of short vowels. In many varieties, such as North Mesopotamian, many Levantine dialects, many Bedouin dialects of the Maghrib, and Mauritanian, short {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} have collapsed to schwa and exhibit very little distinction so that such dialects have two short vowels, {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/ə/}}.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} Many Levantine dialects show partial collapse of {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}}, which appear as such only in the next-to-last phoneme of a word (i.e. followed by a single word-final consonant), and merge to {{IPA|/ə/}} elsewhere.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} A number of dialects that still allow three short vowels {{IPA|/a/}} {{IPA|/i/}} {{IPA|/u/}} in all positions, such as [[Egyptian Arabic]], nevertheless show little functional contrast between {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}} as a result of past sound changes converting one sound into the other.<ref name="Watson 2002 22">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=22}}</ref> Arabic varieties everywhere have a tendency to delete short vowels (especially other than {{IPA|/a/}}) in many phonological contexts. When combined with the operation of [[inflectional morphology]], disallowed consonant clusters often result, which are broken up by [[epenthesis|epenthetic]] short vowels, automatically inserted by phonological rules. In these respects (as in many others), [[Moroccan Arabic]] has the most extreme changes, with all three short vowels {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/i/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} collapsing to a schwa {{IPA|/ə/}}, which is then deleted in nearly all contexts.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} This variety, in fact, has essentially lost the quantitative distinction between short and long vowels in favor of a new qualitative distinction between unstable "reduced" vowels (especially {{IPA|/ə/}}) and stable, half-long "full" vowels {{IPA|/a/}}, {{IPA|/i/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} (the reflexes of original long vowels).{{citation needed|date=April 2011}} [[Classical Arabic]] words borrowed into [[Moroccan Arabic]] are pronounced entirely with "full" vowels regardless of the length of the original vowel.{{citation needed|date=April 2011}}
==Phonologies of different Arabic dialects== The main dialectal variations in Arabic consonants revolve around the six consonants; {{angbr|[[ǧīm|ج]]}}, {{angbr|[[Qāf|ق]]}}, {{angbr|[[Ṯāʾ|ث]]}}, {{angbr|[[Ḏāl|ذ]]}}, {{angbr|[[Ḍād|ض]]}} and {{angbr|[[Ẓāʾ|ظ]]}}:
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center;" |+ !Letter !Classical !Modern Standard ! colspan="3" |Dialectal Main Variations ! rowspan="7" | ! colspan="5" |Less Common Variations |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ث]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/θ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/θ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|θ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|t}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|s}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|f}}</big> | colspan="4" | |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ج]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ɟ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|d͡ʒ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ʒ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|g}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ɟ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|j}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|d͡z}}</big> | colspan="2" | |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ذ]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ð/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ð/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ð}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|d}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|z}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|v}}</big> | colspan="4" | |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ض]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ɮˠ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/dˤ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|dˤ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ðˤ}}</big> | |<big>{{IPAblink|d}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|zˤ}}</big> | colspan="3" | |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ظ]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ðˠ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/ðˤ/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ðˤ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|dˤ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|zˤ}}</big> | colspan="5" | |- |<big>{{script/Arabic|[[ق]]}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/q/}}</big> |<big>{{IPA|/q/}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|q}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|g}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ʔ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|ɢ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|k}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|d͡ʒ}}</big> |<big>{{IPAblink|d͡z}}</big> |<big>[{{IPAlink|ɣ}} ~ {{IPAlink|ʁ}}]</big> |- |}
===Cairene=== {{main|Egyptian Arabic}} The Arabic of [[Cairo]] (often called "[[Egyptian Arabic]]" or more correctly "Cairene Arabic") is a typical sedentary variety and a de facto standard variety among certain segments of the Arabic-speaking population, due to the dominance of Egyptian media. Watson adds emphatic labials {{IPA|[mˤ]}} and {{IPA|[bˤ]}}<ref name="Watson 2002 14">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=14}}</ref> and emphatic {{IPA|[rˤ]}}<ref name="Watson 2002 16"/> to Cairene Arabic with marginal phonemic status. Cairene has also merged the interdental consonants with the dental plosives (e.g. {{IPA|/θalaːθa/}} → {{IPA|[tæˈlæːtæ]}}, 'three') except in loanwords from Classical Arabic where they are nativized as sibilant fricatives (e.g. {{IPA|/θaːnawijja/}} → {{IPA|[sænæˈwejja]}}, '[[secondary school]]'). Cairene speakers pronounce {{IPA|/d͡ʒ/}} as {{IPA|[ɡ]}} and [[debuccalization|debuccalized]] {{IPA|/q/}} to {{IPA|[ʔ]}} (again, loanwords from Classical Arabic have reintroduced the earlier sound<ref name="Watson 2002 22"/> or approximated to {{IPA|[k]}} with the front vowel around it {{IPAblink|æ}} changed to the back vowel {{IPAblink|ɑ}}). Classical Arabic diphthongs {{IPA|/aj/}} and {{IPA|/aw/}} became realized as {{IPA|[eː]}} and {{IPA|[oː]}} respectively. Still, Egyptian Arabic sometimes has minimal pairs like {{IPA|[ˈʃæjlæ]}} ('carrying' f.s.) vs {{IPA|[ˈʃeːlæ]}} ('burden'). {{IPA|[ɡeːb]}} 'pocket' + {{IPA|[næ]}} 'our' → collapsing with {{IPA|[ˈɡebnæ]}} which means ('cheese' or 'our pocket'),<ref name="Watson 2002 23">{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=23}}</ref> because Cairene phonology can't have long vowels before two consonants. Cairene also has {{IPAblink|ʒ}} as a marginal phoneme from loanwords from languages other than Classical Arabic.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=21}}</ref>
===Sanaa=== {{see also|Yemeni Arabic#San'ani Arabic dialect}} Varieties such as that of [[Sana'a|Sanaa]], [[Yemen]], are more conservative and retain most phonemic contrasts of Classical Arabic. Sanaani possesses {{IPAblink|ɡ}} as a reflex of Classical {{IPAslink|q}} (which still functions as an emphatic consonant).<ref name="Watson 2002 23"/> In unstressed syllables, Sanaani short vowels may be reduced to {{IPAblink|ə}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Watson|2002|p=40}}</ref> {{IPA|/tˤ/}} is voiced to {{IPA|[dˤ]}} in initial and intervocalic positions.<ref name="Watson 2002 14"/>
===Morocco=== {{See also|Moroccan Arabic}} {{Unreferenced section|date=April 2011}} Of all the mainstream varieties of Arabic, Moroccan Arabic is likely the one that has diverged the most from Classical Arabic, similarly to the position of [[French language|French]] in the [[Romance languages]] and [[English language|English]] among the [[Germanic languages]]. As described above, Moroccan has heavily innovated in its vowel phonology, under heavy Berber influence. Short vowels {{IPA|/a/}} and {{IPA|/i/}} merged into {{IPA|/ə/}}. More recently, most instances of short {{IPA|/u/}} have also merged into {{IPA|/ə/}}; the few that remain are mostly in the vicinity of velars and uvulars, which suggests an alternative analysis with phonemically rounded consonants (e.g. [[Labialization|labiovelar]]s) and only one short vowel {{IPA|/ə/}}. This schwa, in turn, is phonemically deleted in all contexts except directly followed by a single word-final consonant or in some three-consonant words of the shape ''CəCC''. This inevitably results in some very long, complex consonant clusters, which (unlike most other Arabic varieties) Moroccan Arabic is remarkably tolerant of, only tending to insert [[epenthesis|epenthetic]] schwas to break up the clusters at a slow rate of speech. Unlike in other varieties, doubled consonants are never reduced, but are pronounced clearly whether occurring at the beginning of a word, end of a word, between vowels or before or after a consonant. With the collapse of short vowels, speakers no longer perceive a long vs. short distinction in vowels, which has been replaced with a "full" vs. "reduced/unstable" distinction. "Full" vowels (actually pronounced half-long) substitute for both the long and short vowels of Classical Arabic in borrowings; as a result, these borrowings can be immediately identified by their phonology.
A number of other unique or unusual developments have taken place. Stress is, for the most part, not detectable at all; to the extent stressed syllables can be identified, there is often no consistent pattern governing which syllable is stressed. Original {{IPA|/q/}} has split into two phonemes {{IPA|/q/}} and {{IPA|/ɡ/}}, reflecting the origin of Moroccan Arabic as a mixture of a sedentary and Bedouin dialect. Original diphthongs {{IPA|/aj/}}, {{IPA|/aw/}} have merged into full vowels {{IPA|/i/}}, {{IPA|/u/}} rather than generating new vowel qualities; but "long diphthongs" {{IPA|/aj/}}, {{IPA|/aw/}} also exist, best analyzed as a combination of full vowel {{IPA|/a/}} and semivowel. Unlike most other varieties, emphasis not only triggers front/back allophones in {{IPA|/a/}}, but also high/low allophones in {{IPA|/i/}} and {{IPA|/u/}}, and {{IPA|/ə/}} varies between non-emphatic {{IPA|[ɪ̆]}}, emphatic {{IPA|[ə̆]}}, and pharyngeal-environment {{IPA|[ʌ̆]}}. On the other hand, emphasis spreads only as far as the first full vowel in either direction, unlike in most sedentary varieties where emphasis can spread much more widely, sometimes throughout the entire word. For the purposes of emphasis, {{IPA|/r/}} splits completely into non-emphatic {{IPA|/r/}} and emphatic {{IPA|/rˤ/}}, distinguishable mostly by their effects on adjacent vowels; with very few exceptions, the choice of one or another is consistent across all words derived from a given root. Most emphatic/nonemphatic pairs behave similarly, but {{IPA|/t/}} is [[affrication|affricated]] {{IPA|[tˢ]}} while {{IPA|/tˤ/}} is non-affricated {{IPA|[t]}}, so it is always possible to distinguish the two without recourse to their effects on surrounding vowels.
==Distribution== The most frequent consonant phoneme is {{IPA|/r/}}, the rarest is {{IPA|/ðˤ/}}. The frequency distribution of the 28 consonant phonemes, based on the 2,967 triliteral roots listed by Wehr<ref name=Wehr/> is (with the percentage of roots in which each phoneme occurs):
{| class="wikitable" style="text-align: center" ! Phoneme ! Frequency ! rowspan="15" | ! Phoneme ! Frequency |- | {{IPA|/r/}} | 24% | {{IPA|/w/}} | 18% |- | {{IPA|/l/}} | 17% | {{IPA|/m/}} | 17% |- | {{IPA|/n/}} | 17% | {{IPA|/b/}} | 16% |- | {{IPA|/f/}} | 14% | {{IPA|/ʕ/}} | 13% |- | {{IPA|/q/}} | 13% | {{IPA|/d/}} | 13% |- | {{IPA|/s/}} | 13% | {{IPA|/ħ/}} | 12% |- | {{IPA|/j/}} | 12% | {{IPA|/ʃ/}} | 11% |- | {{IPA|/dʒ/}} | 10% | {{IPA|/k/}} | 9% |- | {{IPA|/h/}} | 8% | {{IPA|/z/}} | 8% |- | {{IPA|/tˤ/}} | 8% | {{IPA|/x/}} | 8% |- | {{IPA|/sˤ/}} | 7% | {{IPA|/ʔ/}} | 7% |- | {{IPA|/t/}} | 6% | {{IPA|/dˤ/}} | 5% |- | {{IPA|/ɣ/}} | 5% | {{IPA|/θ/}} | 3% |- | {{IPA|/ð/}} | 3% | {{IPA|/ðˤ/}} | 1% |}
This distribution does not necessarily reflect the actual frequency of occurrence of the phonemes in speech, since pronouns, prepositions and suffixes are not taken into account, and the roots themselves will occur with varying frequency. In particular, {{IPA|/t/}} occurs in several extremely common [[affix]]es (occurring in the marker for second-person or feminine third-person as a [[prefix]], the marker for first-person or feminine third-person as a [[suffix]], and as the second element of [[Arabic grammar#Stem formation|Forms VIII and X]] as an [[infix]]) despite being fifth from last on Wehr's list. The list does give, however, an idea of which phonemes are more marginal than others. Note that the five least frequent letters are among the six letters added to those inherited from the [[Phoenician alphabet]], namely, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḍād]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ṯāʾ]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḫāʾ]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ẓāʾ]]}}, {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ḏāl]]}} and {{transl|ar|DIN|[[ghain|ġayn]]}}.
==Sample== The [[Modern Standard Arabic|Literary Arabic]] sample text is a reading of [[The North Wind and the Sun]] by a speaker who was born in [[Safed]], lived and was educated in [[Beirut]] from age 8 to 15, subsequently studied and taught in [[Damascus]], studied phonetics in Scotland and since then has resided in Scotland and Kuwait.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=37}}</ref>
===Normal orthographic version=== {{rtl-para|ar|كانت ريح الشمال والشمس تتجادلان؛ أي منهما أقوى؟، وإذ بمسافر يطلع متلفعا بعباءة سميكة. فاتفقتا على اعتبار السابق في إجبار المسافر على خلع عباءته الأقوى. عصفت ريح الشمال بأقصى ما استطاعت من قوة. ولكن كلما ازداد العصف ازداد المسافر تدثرا بعباءته، إلى أن أسقط في يد الريح فتخلت عن محاولتها. بعدئذ سطعت الشمس بدفئها، فما كان من المسافر إلا أن خلع عباءته على التو. وهكذا اضطرت ريح الشمال إلى الاعتراف بأن الشمس كانت هي الأقوى.}}
===Diacriticized orthographic version=== {{rtl-para|ar|كَانَتْ رِيحُ الشَّمَالِ وَالشَّمْسُ تَتَجَادَلان؛ أَيٌٍّ مِنْهُمَا أَقْوَى؟، وَإِذْ بِمُسَافِرٍ يَطْلُعُ مُتَلَفِّعًا بِعَبَاءَةٍ سَمِيكَةٍ. فَاتَّفَقَتَا عَلَى اعْتِبارِ السَّابِقِ فِي إِجْبارِ المُسَافِرِ عَلَى خَلْعِ عَباءَتِهِ الأَقْوىٰ. عَصَفَتْ رِيحُ الشَّمالِ بِأَقْصَى مَا اسْتَطَاعَتْ مِن قُوَّةٍ. وَلٰكِنْ كُلَّمَا ازْدَادَ العَصْفُ ازْدَادَ المُسَافِرُ تَدَثُّرًا بِعَبَاءَتِهِ، إِلَى أَنْ أُسْقِطَ فِي يَدِ الرِّيحِ فَتَخَلَّتْ عَنْ مُحَاوَلَتِهَا. بَعْدَئِذٍ سَطَعَتِ الشَّمْسُ بِدِفْئِهَا، فَمَا كَانَ مِنَ المُسَافِرِ إلَّا أَنْ خَلَعَ عَبَاءَتَهُ عَلَى التَّوِّ. وَهٰكَذَا اضْطُرَّتْ رِيحُ الشَّمَالِ إِلَى الاِعْتِرَافِ بِأَنَّ الشَّمْسَ كَانَتْ هِيَ الأَقْوَى.<ref name="Thelwall 1990 40">{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=40}}</ref>}}
===Phonemic transcription (with ''[[ʾIʿrab|i‘rāb]]'')=== {{IPA|/kaːnat rijħu ʃːamaːli tatad͡ʒaːdalu wa ʃːamsa fij ʔajːin minhumaː kaːnat ʔaqwaː min alʔuxraː {{!}} wa ʔið bi musaːfirin jatˤluʕu mutalafːiʕan bi ʕabaːʔatin samijka {{!}}{{!}} fa tːafaqataː ʕalaː ʕtibaːri sːaːbiqi fij ʔid͡ʒbaːri lmusaːfiri ʕalaː xalʕi ʕabaːʔatihi lʔaqwaː {{!}}{{!}} ʕasˤafat rijħu ʃːamaːli bi ʔaqsˤaː maː statˤaːʕat min quwːa {{!}}{{!}} wa laːkin kulːamaː zdaːda lʕasˤf izdaːda lmusaːfiru tadaθːuran biʕabaːʔatih {{!}} ʔilaː ʔan ʔusqitˤa fij jadi rːijħ fa taxalːat ʕan muħaːwalatihaː {{!}}{{!}} baʕdaʔiðin satˤaʕati ʃːamsu bidifʔihaː {{!}} fa maːkaːna mina lmusaːfiri ʔilːaː ʔan xalaʕa ʕabaːʔatahu ʕalaː tːawː {{!}}{{!}} wa haːkaðaː dˤtˤurat rijħu ʃːamaːli ʔilaː lʔiʕtiraːfi biʔanːa ʃːamsa kaːnat hija lʔaqwaː/}}<ref name="Thelwall 1990 40">{{Harvcoltxt|Thelwall|1990|p=40}}</ref>
===Phonemic transcription ([[Modern Standard Arabic|without ''i‘rāb'']])=== {{IPA|1=/kaːnat riːħ aʃ ʃamaːl tatadʒaːdal waʃ ʃams<span style="font-family:serif;">I</span> fiː ʔajjɪn minhumaː kaːnat ʔaqwaː min al ʔuxraː {{!}} wa ʔið bi musaːfir jatˤlaʕ mutalaffiʕan bi ʕabaːʔa samiːka {{!}}{{!}} fat tafaqataː ʕala ʕtibaːr is saːbiq fiː ʔidʒbaːr al musaːfir ʕalaː xalʕ<span style="font-family:serif;">I</span> ʕabaːʔatih al ʔaqwaː {{!}}{{!}} ʕasˤafat riːħ aʃ ʃamaːl bi ʔaqsˤaː ma statˤaːʕat min quwwa {{!}}{{!}} wa laːkin kullama zdaːd al ʕasˤf izdaːd al musaːfir tadaθθuran bi ʕabaːʔatih {{!}} ʔilaː ʔan ʔusqitˤ fiː jad ar riːħ fa taxallat ʕan muħaːwalatihaː {{!}}{{!}} baʕdaʔiðin satˤaʕat aʃ ʃams<span style="font-family:serif;">I</span> bi difʔihaː {{!}} fa maː kaːn min al musaːfir ʔillaː ʔan xalaʕa ʕabaːʔatah ʕala ttaww {{!}}{{!}} wa haːkaða dˤtˤurrat riːħ aʃ ʃamaːl ʔila lʔiʕtiraːf biʔann aʃ ʃams<span style="font-family:serif;">I</span> kaːnat hija lʔaqwaː/}}
===Phonetic transcription ([[Egyptian Arabic phonology|Egypt]])=== {{IPA|[ˈkæːnæt ɾiːħ æʃ ʃæˈmæːl tætæˈɡæːdæl wæʃ ˈʃæm.se fiː ˈʔæj.jin menˈhomæ ˈkæːnæt ˈʔɑqwɑ mɪn æl ˈʔʊxɾɑ {{!}} wæ ʔɪð bi mʊˈsæːfeɾ ˈjɑtˤlɑʕ mʊtæˈlæf.feʕ bi ʕæˈbæːʔæ sæˈmiːkæ {{!}}{{!}} fæt tæfɑqɑˈtæː ˈʕælæ ʕ.teˈbɑːɾ ɪs ˈsɑːbeq fiː ʔeɡbɑːɾ æl mʊˈsæːfeɾ ˈʕælæ ˈxælʕe ʕæbæːˈʔæt(i)hi lˈʔɑqwɑː {{!}}{{!}} ˈʕɑsˤɑfɑt ɾiːħ æʃ ʃæˈmæːl bi ˈʔɑqsˤɑ mæ stæˈtˤɑːʕɑt mɪn ˈqow.wɑ {{!}}{{!}} wæ ˈlæːkɪn kʊlˈlæmæ zˈdæːd æl ʕɑsˤf ɪzˈdæːd æl mʊˈsæːfeɾ tædæθˈθʊɾæn bi ʕæbæːˈʔætih {{!}} ˈʔilæ ʔæn ˈʔosqetˤ fiː jæd æɾˈɾiːħ fæ tæˈxæl.læt ʕæn mʊħæːwæˈlæt(i)hæ {{!}}{{!}} bæʕdæˈʔiðin ˈsɑtˤɑʕɑt æʃ ˈʃæm.se bi dɪfˈʔihæ {{!}} fæ mæː kæːn mɪn æl mʊˈsæːfeɾ ˈʔil.læ ʔæn ˈxælæʕ ʕæbæːˈʔætæh ʕælætˈtæw {{!}}{{!}} wæ hæːˈkæðæ tˈtˤoɾ.ɾɑt ɾiːħ æʃ ʃæˈmæːl ˈʔilæ lʔeʕteˈɾɑːf biˈʔænn æʃ ˈʃæm.se ˈkæːnæt ˈhɪ.jæ lˈʔɑqwɑ]}}
===ALA-LC transliteration=== {{transl|ar|ALA|Kānat rīḥ al-shamāl tatajādalu wa-al-shams fī ayyin minhumā kānat aqwá min al-ukhrá, wa-idh bi-musāfir yaṭlaʻu mutalaffiʻ bi-ʻabāʼah samīkah. Fa-ittafaqatā ʻalá iʻtibār al-sābiq fī ijbār al-musāfir ʻalá khalʻ ʻabāʼatihi al-aqwá. ʻAṣafat rīḥ al-shamāl bi-aqṣá mā istaṭāʻat min qūwah. Wa-lākin kullamā izdāda al-ʻaṣf izdāda al-musāfir tadaththuran bi-ʻabāʼatih, ilá an usqiṭ fī yad al-rīḥ fa-takhallat ʻan muḥāwalatihā. Baʻdaʼidhin saṭaʻat al-shams bi-difʼihā, fa-mā kāna min al-musāfir illā an khalaʻa ʻabāʼatahu ʻalá al-taww. Wa-hākadhā iḍṭurrat rīḥ al-shamāl ilá al-iʻtirāf bi-an al-shams kānat hiya al-aqwá.}}
===English Wiktionary transliteration (based on Hans Wehr)=== {{transl|ar|Wehr|kānat rīḥu š-šamāli tatajādalu wa-š-šamsa fī ʾayyin minhumā kānat ʾaqwā mina l-ʾuḵrā, wa-ʾiḏ bi-musāfirin yaṭluʿu mutalaffiʿan bi-ʿabāʾatin samīkatin. fa-t-tafaqatā ʿalā ʿtibāri s-sābiqi fī ʾijbāri l-musāfiri ʿalā ḵalʿi ʿabāʾatihi l-ʾaqwā. ʿaṣafat rīḥu š-šamāli bi-ʾaqṣā mā staṭāʿat min quwwatin. walākin kullamā zdāda l-ʿaṣfu zdāda l-musāfiru tadaṯṯuran bi-ʿabāʾatihi, ʾilā ʾan ʾusqiṭa fī yadi r-rīḥi fataḵallat ʿan muḥāwalatihā. baʿdaʾiḏin saṭaʿati š-šamsu bi-difʾihā, famā kāna mina l-musāfiri ʾillā ʾan ḵalaʿa ʿabāʾatahu ʿalā t-tawwi. wa-hakaḏā ḍṭurrat rīḥu š-šamāli ʾilā l-ʾiʿtirāfi biʾanna š-šamsa kānat hiya l-ʾaqwā.}}
