[[File:Tomokichi Fukurai psychic photography.png|thumb|right|220x220px|An alleged "thought photograph" obtained by Tomokichi Fukurai.]] '''Thoughtography,''' also called '''projected thermography,''' '''psychic photography,''' '''nengraphy''', and '''nensha''' {{nihongo||念写||lead=yes}}, is the claimed ability to "burn" images from one's mind onto surfaces such as photographic film by [[Psychokinesis|psychic]] means.<ref name="Krauss">{{cite book|last1=Krauss|first1=Rolf H.|title=Beyond Light and Shadow: The Role of Photography in Certain Paranormal Phenomena: An Historical Survey|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=wCzXAAAAMAAJ&dq=Beyond+Light+and+Shadow%3A+The+Role+of+Photography+in+Certain+Paranormal+Phenomena%3A+An+Historical+Survey&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=thoughtography|date=1995|publisher=[[Nazraeli Press]]|location=Munich|isbn=9783923922383|page=57}}</ref> While the term "thoughtography" has been in the English lexicon since 1913, the more recent term "projected thermography" is a [[neologism]] popularized in the 2002 U.S. film ''[[The Ring (2002 film)|The Ring]]'', a remake of the 1998 Japanese horror film ''[[Ring (film)|Ring]]''.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Lowenstein|first1=Adam|title=Dreaming of Cinema: Spectatorship, Surrealism, and the Age of Digital Media|date=2015|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=9780231538480|pages=124-|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tU8xBgAAQBAJ&pg=PT124|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en}}</ref>
==History== Thoughtography (also known as psychic photography) first emerged in the late 19th century due to the influence of [[spirit photography]].<ref name="Krauss"/> Thoughtography has no connection with Spiritualism, which distinguishes it from spirit photography.<ref name="Chéroux">{{cite book|last1=Chéroux|first1=Clément|title=The Perfect Medium: Photography and the Occult|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EfBf1dNkadoC&printsec=frontcover&dq=The+Perfect+Medium:+Photography+and+the+Occult.&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiWsO_Rq_TXAhUxY98KHYJODnUQ6AEIJjAA#v=onepage&q=Thoughtography&f=false|date=2005|publisher=[[Yale University Press]]|location=New Haven, Connecticut|isbn=9780300111361|page=155}}</ref> One of the first books to mention "psychic photography" was the book ''The New Photography'' (1896) by Arthur Brunel Chatwood. In the book Chatwood described experiments where the "image of objects on the retina of the human eye might so affect it that a photograph could be produced by looking at a sensitive plate."<ref>Arthur Brunel Chatwood. (1896). ''The New Photography''. Downey. p. 93</ref> The book was criticized in a review in ''[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]''.<ref>[[Norman Lockyer]]. (1896). ''Nature''. Volume 53. p. 460</ref>
The psychical researcher [[Hereward Carrington]] in his book ''Modern Psychical Phenomena'' (1919) wrote that many psychic photographs were revealed to be fraudulent produced by substitution and manipulation of the plates, double-printing, double-exposure and chemical screens. However, Carrington also stated he believed some of the photographs to be genuine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/modernpsychicalp00carruoft#page/125/mode/2up |title=Modern psychical phenomena, recent researches and speculations |publisher=[[Internet Archive]] |date=2010-07-21 |accessdate=2016-12-17}}</ref> The term "thoughtography" was first introduced at the beginning of the twentieth century by Tomokichi Fukurai.<ref name="Chéroux"/>
Skeptics, among them professional photographers, consider psychic photographs to be faked or the result of flaws in the camera or film, exposures, film-processing errors, [[lens flare]]s, flash reflections or chemical reactions.<ref name="Nickell">{{cite book|last1=Nickell|first1=Joe|authorlink=Joe Nickell|title=Camera Clues: A Handbook for Photographic Investigation|date=2005|publisher=[[University Press of Kentucky]]|location=Lexington|isbn=9780813191249|page=195}}</ref><ref name="Stein">{{cite book|last1=Stein|first1=Gordon|authorlink=Gordon Stein|title=The Encyclopedia of the Paranormal|date=1996|publisher=Prometheus Books|location=Amherst, New York|isbn=9781573920216|page=517|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Brugioni|first1=Dino A.|authorlink=Dino Brugioni|title=Photo Fakery: A History of Deception and Manipulation|date=1999|publisher=Brassey's|location=Dulles, Virginia|isbn=9781574881660|page=160|edition=1st}}</ref><ref name="skeptic">{{cite book|last1=Carroll|first1=Robert Todd|title=The Skeptic's Dictionary: A Collection of Strange Beliefs, Amusing Deceptions, and Dangerous Delusions|date=2003|publisher=[[John Wiley & Sons|Wiley]]|location=Hoboken, New Jersey|isbn=9780471272427|url=http://www.skepdic.com/pphotog.html|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>
==Claims==
===Tomokichi Fukurai=== Around 1910, during a period of interest in [[Spiritualism]] in Japan, Tomokichi Fukurai, an assistant professor of psychology at [[Tokyo University]] began pursuing [[parapsychology]] experiments using [[Chizuko Mifune]], Ikuko Nagao, and others as subjects. Fukurai published results of experiments with Nagao that alleged she was capable of telepathically imprinting images on photo plates, which he called ''nensha.'' When journalists found irregularities, Nagao's credibility was attacked, and there was speculation that her later illness and death was caused by distress over criticism.<ref name="Lacefield">{{cite book|author=Kristen Lacefield|title=The Scary Screen: Media Anxiety in the Ring|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_qEQNgGCktYC&pg=PA37|date=1 April 2013|publisher=[[Ashgate Publishing]]|isbn=9781409476191|pages=34, 37–|quote=Later that year Fukurai began to study another psychic, Ikuko Nagao, who possessed a talent he called "nenagraphy" or simply ''nensha.'' Fukurai coined this term from the Japanese ''nen,'' meaning "thought" or "idea," and the Greek ''graphein,'' meaning "writing" or "representation," intending it to refer to the power of inscribing images directly onto photographic plates by sheer force of will. This phenomena was known among western psychical researchers as "psychography" or "thoughtography," a practice that first emerged with the discovery of so-called "N-rays" around the turn of the century.|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> In 1913, Fukurai published ''Clairvoyance and Thoughtography''. The book was criticized for a lack of scientific approach and his work disparaged by the university and his colleagues. Fukurai eventually resigned in 1913.<ref name="Baker">{{cite book|author=David B. Baker|title=The Oxford Handbook of the History of Psychology: Global Perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=cAo10l_RTrEC&pg=PA354|date=13 January 2012|publisher=[[Oxford University Press]] |isbn=9780195366556|pages=354–|accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref>
===Eva Carrière=== [[File:Eva C fake ectoplasm made from newspaper.gif|thumb|right|Carrière with fake ectoplasm made from the French magazine ''Le Miroir.'']] In the early 20th century the psychical researcher [[Albert von Schrenck-Notzing]] investigated the medium [[Eva Carrière]] and claimed her [[Ectoplasm (paranormal)|ectoplasm]] "[[Materialization (paranormal)|materializations]]" were the result of "ideoplasty" in which the medium could form images onto ectoplasm from her mind.<ref name="Brady">{{cite book|last1=Brower|first1=M. Brady|title=Unruly Spirits: The Science of Psychic Phenomena in Modern France.|date=2010|publisher=University of Illinois Press|location=Urbana|isbn=9780252077517|page=120}}</ref> Schrenck-Notzing published the book ''Phenomena of Materialisation'' (1923) which included photographs of the ectoplasm. Critics pointed out the photographs of the ectoplasm revealed marks of magazine cut-outs, pins and a piece of string.<ref name="Heredia">{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/spiritismcommons00here#page/186/mode/2up |title=Spiritism and common sense |publisher=Archive.org |date=2010-07-21 |accessdate=2016-12-17}}</ref> Schrenck-Notzing admitted that on several occasions Carrière deceptively smuggled pins into the séance room.<ref name="Heredia"/> The magician [[Carlos María de Heredia]] replicated the ectoplasm of Carrière using a comb, gauze and a handkerchief.<ref name="Heredia"/>
[[Donald J. West|Donald West]] wrote that the [[ectoplasm (paranormal)|ectoplasm]] of Carrière was fake and was made of cut-out paper faces from [[newspaper]]s and [[magazine]]s on which fold marks could sometimes be seen from the photographs. A photograph of Carrière taken from the back of the ectoplasm face revealed it to be made from a magazine cut out with the letters "Le Miro". The two-dimensional face had been clipped from the French magazine Le Miroir.<ref>[[Donald J. West|West, Donald]]. (1954). ''Psychical Research Today''. Chapter Séance-Room Phenomena. Duckworth. p. 49</ref> Back issues of the magazine also matched some of Carrière's ectoplasm faces.<ref>{{cite book|last1=McHargue|first1=Georgess|authorlink=Georgess McHargue|title=Facts, Frauds, and Phantasms: A Survey of the Spiritualist Movement|date=1972|publisher=[[Doubleday (publisher)|Doubleday]]|isbn=0385053053|page=187}}</ref> Cut out faces that she used included [[Woodrow Wilson]], [[Ferdinand I of Bulgaria|King Ferdinand of Bulgaria]], French president [[Raymond Poincaré]] and the actress Mona Delza.<ref name="Stein"/>{{rp|520}}
After Schrenck-Notzing discovered Carrière had taken her ectoplasm faces from the magazine he defended her by claiming she had read the magazine but her memory had recalled the images and they had materialized into the ectoplasm.<ref name="Brady"/> Schrenck-Notzing was described as credulous.<ref name="Heredia"/> [[Joseph McCabe]] wrote "In Germany and Austria, Baron von Schrenck-Notzing is the laughing-stock of his medical colleagues."<ref>{{cite book|last1=Harris|first1=Frank|title=Debates on the Meaning of Life, Evolution and Spiritualism|date=1993|publisher=[[Prometheus Books]]|location=Buffalo, New York|isbn=9780879758288|page=77}}</ref>
===Ted Serios=== {{main|Ted Serios}} In the 1960s, it was claimed that [[Chicago]] resident [[Ted Serios]], a hotel bellhop in his late forties, used [[Psychokinesis|psychokinetic]] powers to produce images on [[Instant film|Polaroid]] instant film.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Nickell|first1=Joe|title=Camera Clues: a Handbook for Photographic Investigation.|date=2010|publisher=University Press of Kentucky|location=Lexington|isbn=0813138280|page=197|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZMCQ7YHw4CgC&pg=PA197&dq=thoughtography+psychokinesis&hl=en&sa=X&ei=x-aMUvvAK4Tm2gW8j4CIDw&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=thoughtography%20psychokinesis&f=false|quote=Psychokinetic Photographs. In 1967 the world learned of a Chicago man with apparently remarkable powers: he could merely ''think'' of pictures and cause them to appear on photographic film -- a supposedly psychokinetic (PK) process called "thoughtography." The man, an often unemployed bellhop named Ted Serios, was the object of a sensational article in ''Life'' magazine and even an entire book written by Denver psychiatrist Jule Eisenbud, ''The World of Ted Serios.'' To accomplish his marvelous feat, Serios looked through a paper tube that he pressed against the camera's lens. A Polaroid model was used . . . |accessdate=11 February 2017}}</ref> Serios's psychic claims were bolstered by the endorsement of a [[Denver]]-based psychiatrist, Jule Eisenbud (1908–1999), who wrote a book, ''The World of Ted Serios: "Thoughtographic" Studies of an Extraordinary Mind'' (1967), arguing that Serios's purported psychic abilities were genuine.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Kripal|first1=Jeffrey J.|title=Authors of the Impossible: The Paranormal and the Sacred|date=2011|publisher=University of Chicago Press|location=Chicago, Illinos|isbn=9780226453897|pages=285|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5wD5hS03NkgC&pg=PA285|accessdate=6 December 2017|language=en}}</ref> However, professional photographers and skeptics found that Serios was employing simple [[sleight of hand]].<ref name="Hines">{{cite book|last1=Hines|first1=Terence|authorlink=Terence Hines|title=Pseudoscience and the paranormal|date=2002|publisher=Prometheus Books|location=Amherst, New York|isbn=9781573929790|page=77|edition=2nd}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=http://chronicle.com/article/Psychic-Projections-Were-a/126934/ |title='Psychic Projections' Were a Hoax - The Chronicle of Higher Education |publisher=Chronicle.com |date= |accessdate=2016-12-17 |quote=Anyone who knows anything about this issue knows that Mr. Serios was long ago exposed and thoroughly debunked as a fraud. This was done with absolute certainty by professional photographers Charlie Reynolds and David Eisendrath in the October 1967 issue of Popular Photography. Serios was observed, when he thought no one was looking, sticking pictures into his "gizmo," a tube he held between his head and the camera lens. That some claim he produced images without the tube, and at some distance from the camera, is easily attributed to double exposure or use of previously made exposures, followed by the fake snapping of a picture.}}</ref>
===Masuaki Kiyota=== {{main|Masuaki Kiyota}}
Masuaki Kiyota is a Japanese psychic who was claimed to possess [[psychokinesis|psychokinetic]] powers.<ref name="Kurtz">{{cite book|author=Paul Kurtz|title=A Skeptic's Handbook of Parapsychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LQh_AAAAMAAJ|year=1985|publisher=Prometheus Books|location=Buffalo, New York|page=348|isbn=9780879753009}}</ref><ref name="Nickell"/>{{rp|198}} Kiyota was tested by investigators in [[London]] by [[ITV Granada|Granada Television]] and the results were negative. It was discovered that with tight controls, Kiyota was unable to project mental images onto film. He could only achieve success when he had the film in his possession without any control for at least 2 hours.<ref name="Nickell"/>{{rp|198}}
According to magician and skeptic [[James Randi]] "Kiyota's Polaroid photos were apparently produced by preexposing the film, since it was noted that he made great efforts to obtain a film pack and spend time with it in private."<ref>{{cite web|title=K - Encyclopedia of Claims|url=http://web.randi.org/k---encyclopedia-of-claims.html|website=James Randi Educational Foundation|accessdate=6 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last1=Randi|first1=James|authorlink=James Randi|title=[[An Encyclopedia of Claims, Frauds, and Hoaxes of the Occult and Supernatural]]|date=1995|publisher=[[St. Martin's Press]]|location=New York|isbn=0312151195|edition=1st}}</ref> In a 1984 television interview, Kiyota confessed to fraud.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Melton|first1=J. Gordon|authorlink=J. Gordon Melton|last2=Shepard|first2=Leslie|title=Encyclopedia of Occultism and Parapsychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jn9IPgAACAAJ&dq=Encyclopedia+of+Occultism+and+Parapsychology&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiH7sPVqvTXAhWiY98KHWtSCNMQ6AEIKjAB|archiveurl=http://www.eso-garden.com/specials/encyclopedia_of_occultism_and_parapsychology_1.pdf|archivedate=November 1, 2010|date=2001|publisher=[[Gale Research Company]]|location=Detroit, Michigan|isbn=081039488X|edition=5th|page=865|quote=Randi's point was driven home in 1984 when Masuaki Kiyota, hailed as the Japanese Uri Geller, revealed in a television interview that he had faked the phenomena that had been verified by both American and Japanese researchers.}}</ref>
===Uri Geller=== {{main|Uri Geller}} In 1995, famed psychic [[Uri Geller]] began to use a 35&nbsp;mm [[camera]] in his performances. The lens cap left on the camera, Geller would take pictures of his forehead and then have the pictures developed. Geller claimed that subsequent images had come directly from his mind.<ref name="skeptic"/>{{rp|313}} James Randi claimed Geller had performed the trick by using a "handheld optical device" or by taking photographs on already exposed film.<ref name="skeptic"/>{{rp|313}}
