* {{IPA|/m, mʲ, p, pʲ, b, bʲ, β, ɥ/}} are [[Bilabial consonant|bilabial]], whereas {{IPA|/f, v/}} are [[Labiodental consonant|labiodental]].{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=35–37, 41, 46}}
** {{IPA|/mʲ, pʲ, bʲ/}} are strongly palatalized.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=41}}
** {{IPA|/β/}} is a somewhat velarized bilabial approximant {{IPAblink|β̞|β̞ˠ}}, whereas {{IPA|/ɥ/}} (the soft counterpart of {{IPA|/β/}}) is a strongly palatalized bilabial approximant {{IPAblink|ɥ}}.<ref>{{Harvcoltxt|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=36–37, 41, 46}}. On page 36, the author states that Upper Sorbian {{IPA|/β/}} is less velar than Polish {{IPA|/w/}}. The weakness of the velarization is confirmed by the corresponding image on page 37.</ref>
** {{IPA|/v/}} is very rare. Apart from loanwords, it occurs only in two Slavonic words: ''zełharny'' {{IPA|/ˈzɛvaʀni/}} 'deceitful' and ''zełharnosć'' {{IPA|/ˈzɛvaʀnɔst͡ʃ/}} 'deceitfulness', both of which are derivatives of ''łhać'' {{IPA|/ˈfat͡ʃ/}} 'to lie'. Usage of these words is typically restricted to the [[Bautzen]] dialect, as speakers of the Catholic dialect use ''łžeć'' {{IPA|/ˈbʒɛt͡ʃ/}} and its derivatives.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=36}}{{sfnp|Stone|2002|pp=603–604}}
* {{IPA|/n, l/}} are alveolar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|n|n̳}}, {{IPA link|l|l̳}}]}}, {{IPA|/ɲ/}} is [[Alveolo-palatal consonant|alveolo-palatal]] {{IPAblink|ɲ̟}}, whereas {{IPA|/t, d, t͡s, d͡z, t͡sʲ, s, z, zʲ/}} are dental {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪}}, {{IPA link|t̪͡s̪}}, {{IPA link|d̪͡z̪}}, t̪͡s̪ʲ, {{IPA link|s̪}}, {{IPA link|z̪}}, z̪ʲ]}}.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=600}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=37–41, 46}}{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|pp=190–191}}
** {{IPA|/t, d, l/}} before {{IPA|/i/}} (in the case of {{IPA|/l/}} also before {{IPA|/e, ɛ/}}) are weakly palatalized {{IPA|[tʲ, dʲ, lʲ]}}. {{Harvcoltxt|Šewc-Schuster|1984}} also reports palatalized allophones of {{IPA|/f, v, k, ɡ, x, ɦ/}}, but without specifying the vowels before which they occur.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=37, 39, 46}} Among these, the palatalized {{IPA|[fʲ, vʲ]}} are extremely rare.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=604}}
** {{IPA|/n, nʲ/}} are velar {{IPA|[{{IPA link|ŋ}}, ŋʲ]}} in front of velar consonants.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=39, 46}}
** {{IPA|/d͡z/}} is very rare. In many cases, it merges with {{IPA|/z/}} into {{IPAblink|z̪|z}}.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=38}}{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|p=191}}
** {{IPA|/t͡sʲ, zʲ/}} are very rare.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=38}}{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|p=191}} According to {{Harvcoltxt|Stone|2002}}, the phonemic status of {{IPA|/t͡sʲ/}} is controversial.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=604}}
* In most dialects, {{IPA|/t͡ʃ, d͡ʒ, ʃ, ʒ/}} are [[Palato-alveolar consonant|palato-alveolar]]. This is unlike Lower Sorbian, where these consonants are laminal retroflex (flat postalveolar) {{IPA|[{{IPA link|t͡ʂ}}, {{IPA link|ʂ}}, {{IPA link|ʐ}}]}} (Lower Sorbian {{IPA|/t͡ʂ/}} does not have a voiced counterpart).{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=40–41}}{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|pp=180–181, 190–191}} Laminal retroflex realizations of {{IPA|/ʃ, ʒ/}}{{fix|text=what about the affricates {{IPA|/t͡ʃ, d͡ʒ/}}?|date=August 2015}} also occur in Upper Sorbian dialects spoken in some villages north of [[Hoyerswerda]].{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=41}}{{sfnp|Zygis|2003|p=180}}
* {{IPA|/k, ɡ, x/}} are velar, whereas {{IPA|/ʀ, ʀʲ/}} are uvular.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|pp=600, 602}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=42–44, 46}}
** An aspirated {{IPA|[kʰ]}} is a morpheme-initial allophone of {{IPA|/x/}} in some cases, as well as a possible word-initial allophone of {{IPA|/k/}}.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=26–27, 42–43}}
** {{IPA|/x/}} does not occur word-initially, whereas {{IPA|/ɦ/}} does not occur word-finally.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=43}}
** The alveolar realization {{IPA|[{{IPA link|r|r̳}}, r̳ʲ]}} of {{IPA|/ʀ, ʀʲ/}} is archaic.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=602}}
** Soft {{IPA|/ʀʲ/}} is strongly palatalized.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=41}}
* {{IPA|/ɦ/}} is voiced {{IPAblink|ɦ}}, unlike Lower Sorbian where it is voiceless {{IPAblink|h}}.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|pp=600, 605}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|pp=43, 46}}
* An epenthetic {{IPA|/j/}} is inserted before a post-vocalic soft consonant, yielding a diphthong. If the soft consonant occurs before {{IPA|/ɛ/}} or {{IPA|/e/}}, it is often realized as hard, and {{IPA|/e/}} is lowered to {{IPA|[ɛ]}}.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=604}}{{examples needed|date=August 2017}}
* In literary language, the contrast between hard and soft consonants is neutralized in word-final position. Word-finally, the letter {{angle bracket|ń}} represents a post-vocalic sequence {{IPA|/jn/}}, as in ''dźeń'' {{IPA|/ˈd͡ʒɛjn/}} 'day'.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=604}}

===Final devoicing and assimilation===
{{Expand section|date=April 2015}}
Upper Sorbian has both [[final devoicing]] and regressive [[phonation|voicing]] [[assimilation (linguistics)|assimilation]], both word-internal and across word boundaries.{{sfnp|Stone|2002|p=604}}{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=26}} In the latter context, {{IPA|/x/}} is voiced to {{IPAblink|ɣ}}. Regressive voicing assimilation does not occur before [[Sonorant|sonorants]] and {{IPA|/ɦ/}}.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=26}}

==Stress==
{{Expand section|date=April 2015}}
* Words consisting of up to three syllables are stressed on the first syllable.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=27}}
* Foreign words, such as ''student'' {{IPA|/stuˈdɛnt/}} 'student', preserve their original accent.{{sfnp|Šewc-Schuster|1984|p=28}}

